{
 "id": "exponent_rules",
 "name": "Exponent Rules",
 "unit": "5 — Exponents & Polynomials",
 "description": "The student can apply the core exponent rules — product rule (xᵃ · xᵇ = xᵃ⁺ᵇ), power rule ((xᵃ)ᵇ = xᵃᵇ), quotient rule (xᵃ / xᵇ = xᵃ⁻ᵇ), and negative exponent rule (x⁻ⁿ = 1/xⁿ) — to simplify expressions involving multiple exponent operations in a single combined expression. Law 4 numeric entry point: each rule transforms the shape of the expression while preserving its value.\n",
 "unlock_condition": "mastery >= 0.8 on all required skills, confirmed by boss challenge",
 "mastery_threshold": 0.8,
 "skills_required": [
  "structure_preserved",
  "show_work_minimum"
 ],
 "boss_challenge": {
  "id": "boss_exponent_rules_v1",
  "task_description": "Simplify: (x²)³ · x⁻¹ / x⁴. Show each exponent rule you apply as a separate step. State the rule used (product, power, quotient, or negative exponent) beside each step. Write your final answer with a positive exponent.\n",
  "sensor_purpose": "Four exponent rules must be applied sequentially in the correct order — power rule first on (x²)³, then product rule to combine with x⁻¹, then quotient rule to divide by x⁴. The canonical Law 4 failure: applying (x²)³ as x⁵ (adding exponents instead of multiplying) — the expression's shape changes incorrectly. The rule-naming requirement ensures the student is not pattern-matching but actively categorising each transformation. Naming a rule incorrectly while applying it correctly is a signal that the student can execute but cannot articulate the structural principle.\n",
  "grading": [
   {
    "check": "structure_preserved",
    "weight": 0.5
   },
   {
    "check": "correct_final_value",
    "weight": 0.35
   },
   {
    "check": "step_count >= 3",
    "weight": 0.15
   }
  ],
  "pass_threshold": 0.8,
  "hints_allowed": false,
  "max_attempts_per_session": 1
 }
}

{
 "id": "polynomial_operations",
 "name": "Polynomial Operations — Expansion",
 "unit": "5 — Exponents & Polynomials",
 "description": "The student can multiply two binomials using FOIL (First, Outer, Inner, Last), ensuring all four partial products are computed before collecting like terms. They can also add and subtract polynomials by combining only like-degree terms. Law 4 assembly: the product form and the expanded form are two shapes of the same expression. FOIL is the systematic procedure that guarantees the transformation is structure-preserving.\n",
