  "solution_verifies",
  "show_work_minimum"
 ],
 "boss_challenge": {
  "id": "boss_quadratic_equations_v1",
  "task_description": "Part A — Algebraic:\n  Solve x² − 5x + 6 = 0.\n  (1) Solve by factoring — find the factored form and state both roots.\n  (2) Confirm both roots using the quadratic formula x = (−b ± √(b²−4ac)) / 2a.\n      Show the discriminant calculation separately.\n  (3) Verify each root by substituting into the original equation.\n\nPart B — Word Problem (Law 6 sensor):\n  A rectangular garden has a length that is 3 meters more than its width.\n  The area of the garden is 40 square meters.\n  (1) Define your variable. Write an equation for the area.\n  (2) Rearrange into standard form ax² + bx + c = 0 and solve.\n  (3) State which solution is valid in context and explain why.\n",
  "sensor_purpose": "Part A is the Laws 1+2+3+4 integration test. x = 2 and x = 3 (roots of (x−2)(x−3)) are close enough that a student guessing can produce one correct root — the quadratic formula confirmation in step (2) and the dual substitution verification in step (3) rule out lucky guessing. The discriminant must be shown separately (b²−4ac = 25−24 = 1) to make the arithmetic of the formula transparent. Part B is the terminal Law 6 sensor. The garden problem has two natural transcription failure modes: writing w(w+3) = 40 is correct; writing (w+3)w = 40 is also correct (commutative) but many students write w + (w+3) = 40 (confusing area with perimeter) or w·3 = 40 (ignoring the width as a factor). Setting the area equation up correctly, rearranging to standard form (w² + 3w − 40 = 0), factoring to (w+8)(w−5) = 0, and rejecting w = −8 as non-physical completes all 6 laws in a single problem.\n",
